  "tree-removal/whitfield": {
    heroParagraph: "Professional tree removal in Whitfield — hillside properties backing onto rainforest reserve where mature trees and encroaching native vegetation demand experienced, careful removal. Tipper truck, wood chipper, and 7 years of hands-on experience on every Whitfield job.",
    localContext: "<p>Whitfield is Cairns' rainforest suburb. Properties here back directly onto the Whitfield Conservation Park and the forested hillside of the range. The interface between residential gardens and native bush means trees are constantly encroaching — native species seeding into gardens, canopy branches growing over rooflines, and root systems from bush trees extending into driveways and foundations. It's a suburb where tree removal is a regular maintenance need, not a one-off event.</p><p>The premium homes in Whitfield — along Doolan Street, Ponticello Street, and the streets climbing the hill — have large blocks with mature trees that provide privacy and character but also create real hazards. Cyclone season is a particular concern: trees weakened by wet season saturation become unstable in high winds, and a falling tree on a hillside property can cause catastrophic damage to the home below. Proactive removal of hazardous trees is far cheaper than storm damage repair.</p><p>Whitfield is only 5km from our Freshwater base, and the terrain is similar to what we work in regularly. We understand hillside access challenges, the native species common on the range, and the need to work carefully near the conservation park boundary. We remove trees on your property — we don't touch anything on public or conservation land.</p>",
    faqs: [
      { q: "How much does tree removal cost in Whitfield?", a: "Small trees from $300-$500. Medium trees $800-$3,000. Large trees on hillside blocks or near rainforest boundary $3,000-$10,000+. Whitfield's steep terrain can add complexity. Free on-site assessment and written quote." },
      { q: "Can you remove trees near the rainforest reserve in Whitfield?", a: "We remove trees on your private property only. We don't touch anything on conservation or council land. If a tree straddles the boundary, we can advise on the right approach and whether council needs to be involved." },
      { q: "Is tree removal harder on Whitfield's steep blocks?", a: "It requires more planning. Steep terrain affects how we fell and lower tree sections, where we position the chipper and tipper, and how we manage debris. We're experienced with hillside work and plan every Whitfield job around the specific terrain." },
      { q: "Do you do cyclone preparation tree removal in Whitfield?", a: "Yes. Whitfield's exposed hillside position and proximity to rainforest make cyclone preparation important. We can assess your property's trees, identify the hazards, and remove or reduce the ones that pose the greatest risk before storm season." },
      { q: "Can you remove native trees that have seeded into my Whitfield garden?", a: "In most cases, yes. Native seedlings and regrowth that have established in your garden are generally fine to remove. Larger native trees may need council assessment depending on species and size. We can advise on the specifics." }
    ]
  },

  "vegetation-management/whitfield": {
    heroParagraph: "Vegetation management in Whitfield — managing the boundary between premium hillside homes and encroaching rainforest. From garden boundary clearing along Doolan Street to undergrowth control on large blocks near the Whitfield Conservation Park, Steady Eco keeps Whitfield properties safe and liveable.",
    localContext: "<p>Living in Whitfield means living with the rainforest — and that means constant vegetation management. The bush doesn't respect property boundaries. Native vines, seedlings, grasses, and undergrowth push into gardens year-round, accelerating dramatically in the wet season. A cleared boundary in dry season can be swallowed by the bush by March. For properties along the conservation park edge, this is an annual battle that requires professional equipment and regular attention.</p><p>Fire preparation is another driver of vegetation management in Whitfield. The hillside location, dense surrounding vegetation, and eucalypt forest above create genuine bushfire risk in the dry season. Maintaining defensible space around your home — cleared undergrowth, managed garden beds, no dead vegetation against structures — is both a safety measure and an insurance expectation. We clear and maintain these buffers efficiently with chipper, mower, and hand tools.</p><p>At just 5km from our Freshwater base, Whitfield is one of our closest suburbs. We service properties here regularly and know the terrain, the vegetation types, and the access challenges on the steeper blocks. Whether it's a one-off boundary clearing or an annual maintenance schedule, we bring the right equipment and get it done properly.</p>",
    faqs: [
      { q: "How much does vegetation management cost in Whitfield?", a: "Garden boundary clearing from $300-$800. Larger block clearing and undergrowth management $1,000-$4,000+ depending on area and density. Annual maintenance schedules available at better rates. Free on-site quotes." },
      { q: "How often should Whitfield properties be cleared?", a: "At minimum annually, ideally twice — once in late dry season (September-October) for fire preparation, and once after the wet season (April-May) to reclaim ground lost to wet season growth. Properties on the conservation park boundary may need three visits." },
      { q: "Do you do bushfire preparation in Whitfield?", a: "Yes. We clear undergrowth, dead material, and overhanging vegetation around your home to create defensible space. This is especially important for Whitfield properties on the hillside where fire risk is higher than in flat suburban areas." },
      { q: "Can you manage the bush encroaching into my Whitfield garden?", a: "Yes. Native regrowth, vines, and seedlings pushing into your garden from the bush edge are a constant issue in Whitfield. We clear back to your boundary, chip the material, and leave a clean garden edge. Regular visits keep it under control." }
    ]
  },

