  "lawn-mowing/edmonton": {
    heroParagraph: "Regular lawn mowing in Edmonton — Cairns' southern growth corridor where new estates need reliable mowing from day one. From freshly turfed blocks off the Bruce Highway to established homes near the Edmonton shopping village, ride-on and push mowing with edging and blowing every visit.",
    localContext: "<p>Edmonton is one of Cairns' fastest-growing areas, with new housing estates spreading south from the existing township. Many properties here are brand new — turf laid within the last few years, gardens still being established, and homeowners who've just taken on a mortgage and don't want to spend every weekend mowing. Regular professional mowing from day one helps new turf establish properly and keeps the property looking sharp without the owner needing their own equipment.</p><p>The established parts of Edmonton — around the shopping village, Walker Road, and the older residential streets — have mature tropical lawns on medium-sized blocks. These are straightforward mowing jobs, but the tropical climate means growth is relentless in the wet season. A tidy Edmonton lawn in November can be knee-high by December if you miss two mows. For rental properties (and there are plenty in Edmonton), regular mowing keeps the landlord happy and the tenants comfortable.</p><p>Edmonton is 12km south on the Bruce Highway — about 15 minutes from our Freshwater base. We service Edmonton on our southern route alongside Bentley Park, Mount Sheridan, and Gordonvale. Regular Edmonton clients get set fortnightly scheduling with the same reliable service every visit.</p>",
    faqs: [
      { q: "How much does lawn mowing cost in Edmonton?", a: "Standard Edmonton residential blocks $60-$80 per mow including edging and blowing. New estate blocks with smaller yards from $50. Larger properties with ride-on mowing $80-$120. All prices confirmed upfront." },
      { q: "Do you mow new lawns on Edmonton estates?", a: "Yes. New turf needs regular mowing from about 3-4 weeks after laying. Fortnightly from the start helps the lawn thicken and establish properly. We mow many properties on the newer Edmonton estates." },
      { q: "Can you mow rental properties in Edmonton?", a: "Yes. We maintain lawns for multiple rental properties and investment properties in Edmonton. Regular fortnightly mowing keeps the property presentable for tenants and ready for inspections. We work with property managers or landlords directly." },
      { q: "How often should Edmonton lawns be mowed?", a: "Fortnightly year-round. Weekly in the wet season (Nov-Apr) for the best results — tropical grass growth in Edmonton is intense when the rain comes. Letting it go three weeks in the wet makes the next mow much harder." },
      { q: "Do you service both old and new Edmonton?", a: "Yes — we service the entire Edmonton area, including the established township around the shopping village, Walker Road, and all the newer estates spreading south. Edmonton is on our regular southern route." }
    ]
  },

  "landscaping/edmonton": {
    heroParagraph: "Professional landscaping in Edmonton — helping new homeowners turn builder-basic yards into proper tropical gardens. From garden installations on fresh estates to renovation of established properties near the Edmonton shopping village, Steady Eco brings practical landscaping knowledge and the right equipment.",
    localContext: "<p>Edmonton's new estates are full of homes with builder-standard yards — basic turf, bare garden beds, and no real landscaping to speak of. The real garden work starts after the builder hands over, and many Edmonton homeowners want practical, affordable landscaping that looks good without costing a fortune. Mulched garden beds with hardy tropical species, clean garden edging, and a few feature plants is the sweet spot — attractive, low-maintenance, and within a young family's budget.</p><p>The older parts of Edmonton have a different need. Established gardens that are 15-20 years old and getting tired, overgrown hedges that haven't been shaped in years, and garden beds that need a complete refresh. The former cane land that Edmonton was built on has good, fertile soil — plants establish quickly here, which means a garden renovation delivers visible results fast.</p><p>Edmonton is 12km south of our Freshwater base and on our regular southern route. We know the local conditions — the soil quality, the drainage patterns on the flat terrain, and the tropical species that establish quickly and require minimal ongoing maintenance. Whether you're starting from scratch on a new build or refreshing an established Edmonton garden, we bring practical solutions that work.</p>",
    faqs: [
      { q: "How much does landscaping cost in Edmonton?", a: "Garden maintenance from $80/hr. New garden installations for Edmonton homes — converting builder-basic yards — typically $1,000-$4,000 depending on size. Full property landscaping and garden renovations quoted per project. Free on-site quotes." },
      { q: "Can you landscape a new Edmonton home?", a: "Yes — it's one of our most common Edmonton jobs. We install complete gardens: plants, mulch, garden edging, soil improvement where needed. We design for low-maintenance and practical use, especially for families with kids and pets." },
      { q: "What affordable plants work in Edmonton?", a: "Lomandras and cordylines for structure (hardy and cheap). Heliconias and bird of paradise for colour. Frangipanis as feature trees. All establish quickly in Edmonton's fertile soil and handle the tropical climate with minimal care." },
      { q: "Do you offer regular garden maintenance in Edmonton?", a: "Yes. Fortnightly maintenance for Edmonton properties — hedging, weeding, mulching, general garden upkeep. Regular clients get priority scheduling on our southern route." },
      { q: "How long does it take to landscape a new Edmonton yard?", a: "Most new Edmonton garden installations take 1-2 days depending on size and scope. Garden bed preparation, planting, mulching, and edging can transform a bare builder yard into a finished garden quickly. Plants establish fast in Edmonton's fertile soil." }
    ]
  },

